                <fr:title text="matrix">matrix</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> be positive integers. We define an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex>-by-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> <html:dfn>Matrix</html:dfn> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> to be a rectangular array of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[mn]]></fr:tex> real [or complex] numbers arranged in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> horizontal <html:dfn>Rows</html:dfn> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> vertical <html:dfn>Columns</html:dfn>, written:
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}
= \left (\begin {array}{cccccc}
  a_{11} & a_{12} & … & a_{1j} & … & a_{1n} \\
a_{21} & a_{22} & … & a_{2j} & … & a_{2n}  \\
\vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\
a_{i1} & a_{i2} & … & a_{ij} & … & a_{in} \\
\vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\
a_{m1} & a_{m2} & …   & a_{mj} & …  & a_{mn} 
\end {array}\right )
\begin {array}{c}
  \\
  \gets  i^{\text {th}}\hbox {\ row}
\end {array}]]></fr:tex>
We have highlighted the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> row, and the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> column.</html:p>
                <html:p>If further <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m=n]]></fr:tex> (so we have an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-by-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> matrix), then we call it a <html:dfn>Square Matrix</html:dfn>. In this case, we can refer to the <html:dfn>Main Diagonal</html:dfn> as the components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{1,1}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{2,2}]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{n,n}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>We abbreviate "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex>-by-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> matrix" as "<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix". The pair of numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(m,n)]]></fr:tex> is called the <html:dfn>Dimensions</html:dfn> of the matrix. (We can also extend our definitions to allow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> to be zero, but these are degenerate edgecases.)</html:p>
                <html:p>Also note, some people use parentheses in writing matrices, other people use square brackets. Both are acceptable.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
