                <fr:route>/matrix-0002/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="components of a matrix">components of a matrix</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>If we want to refer to a generic component of an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex>-by-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> matrix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>, we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}=(a_{ij})]]></fr:tex> to indicate we will use <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{ij}]]></fr:tex> to refer to the component found in the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> row and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j^{\text {th}}]]></fr:tex> column.</html:p>
                <html:p>Also, very important, if we have some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex>-by-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> matrix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}=(a_{i,j})]]></fr:tex> and we wanted to refer to its component in row <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>, column <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c]]></fr:tex>, we may refer to that component by writing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathbf {A})_{r,c}]]></fr:tex>. This is, of course, the same as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{r,c}]]></fr:tex>, but it will be useful [much later] to take a matrix and refer to certain components without introducing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(a_{i,j})]]></fr:tex> first.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
