                <fr:route>/matrix-0006/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="diagonal matrix">diagonal matrix</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A square matrix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}=(a_{i,j})]]></fr:tex> for which <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_{i,j}=0]]></fr:tex> when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i\neq  j]]></fr:tex> is called a <html:dfn>Diagonal Matrix</html:dfn>. We may write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}=\mathrm {diag}(a_{1,1}, a_{2,2},…, a_{n,n})]]></fr:tex> to indicate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> is a diagonal matrix.</html:p>
                <html:p>Caution: some authors write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {diag}(\mathbf {A})]]></fr:tex> to refer to the <html:em>diagonal components</html:em> of any matrix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>. Just bear this in mind when you run into it "in the wild".</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>12</fr:day>
