                <fr:title text="Puzzles about matrix equality">Puzzles about matrix equality</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:ol><html:li>Will every matrix <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>? (Mathematicians call this property "reflexivity", and most "equality-like" relations should have it.)</html:li>
<html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex>, is it true or false that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B} = \mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>? Prove it or find a counter-example.</html:li>
<html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B} = \mathbf {C}]]></fr:tex>, is it true or false that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \mathbf {C}]]></fr:tex>? Prove it or find a counter-example. These first three properties are true for 'equivalence relations' (binary relations which loosely resemble equality).</html:li>
<html:li>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\neq  p]]></fr:tex>. If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\times  n]]></fr:tex> matrix, and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\times  p]]></fr:tex> matrix, then is it true or false that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}=\mathbf {B}]]></fr:tex>?</html:li></html:ol>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
