                <fr:title text="Block Matrix">Block Matrix</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>It is useful to draw horizontal and vertical lines (either dashed or slid, it makes no difference except for typography), to partition a matrix into blocks, permitting us to write
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A} = \left [
    \begin {array}{c:c}
        \mathbf {B} & \mathbf {C} \\ \hdashline 
        \mathbf {D} & \mathbf {E} 
    \end {array}
\right ] = \left [
    \begin {array}{c|c}
        \mathbf {B} & \mathbf {C} \\ \hline 
        \mathbf {D} & \mathbf {E} 
    \end {array}
\right ].]]></fr:tex>
We could partition a matrix however we want, and we call the blocks <html:dfn>Submatrices</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>. Writing <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex> in this manner is called a <html:dfn>Block Decomposition</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {A}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
